{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fa3c9970-894e-4c2e-813a-4ff69cf32c81","content":"This repository doesn't contain specific documentation on that topic, but here's the general guidance:\n\n## Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump`. On macOS you have two options:\n\n### 1. Use macOS's built-in crash reports\nmacOS automatically writes crash logs to:\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\nLook for a `.ips` or `.crash` file matching your process name/timestamp. These contain stack traces but aren't full core dumps.\n\n### 2. Enable core dumps via the kernel\n```bash\n# Allow core files\nulimit -c unlimited\n\n# Check/set core file location\nsudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/cores/core.%P\n\n# Ensure the target directory exists\nsudo mkdir -p /tmp/cores\n\n# Re-run your app — a core file is written on crash\n./MyNativeAotApp\n```\n\nThen analyze with `lldb`:\n```bash\nlldb ./MyNativeAotApp -c /tmp/cores/core.<pid>\n```\n\n> **Note:** On Apple Silicon, you may need to codesign your binary with the `com.apple.security.get-task-allow` entitlement for core dumps to be generated. SIP (System Integrity Protection) can also block core dumps for certain paths.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"41ccbec2-98a0-4558-99b5-1d4271a26186","outputTokens":318,"requestId":"9430:100381:25DFC1:2D21EA:69E8201F"},"id":"0dd61268-88f0-4a89-adeb-c09e54b83fc1","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:11:05.091Z","parentId":"85b6a2de-d3ab-45b7-9318-207970e8aa37"}
